-fol|after=[[Autumn Phillips]]}}\n{{end}}\n{{Meghan, Duchess of Sussex}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list=\n{{British princesses by marriage}}\n{{UK Order of Precedence (Ladies)}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Royalty|United Kingdom|United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meghan, Duchess of Sussex}}\n[[Category:Meghan, Duchess of Sussex| ]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women]]\n[[Category:20th-century Protestants]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women]]\n[[Category:21st-century Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Hollywood, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Immaculate Heart High School, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American Anglicans]]\n[[Category:American calligraphers]]\n[[Category:American emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:American expatriate actresses in Canada]]\n[[Category:American feminists]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:British baronesses|Kilkeel]]\n[[Category:British countesses|Dumbarton]]\n[[Category:British duchesses by marriage|Sussex]]\n[[Category:British feminists]]\n[[Category:Converts to Anglicanism]]\n[[Category:Game show models]]\n[[Category:House of Windsor]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Markle family|Meghan]]\n[[Category:Mountbatten-Windsor family]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from View Park\u2013Windsor Hills, California]]\n[[Category:Wives of British princes]]\n[[Category:Women calligraphers]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 -WP:WCWproject (Unbalanced quotes in ref name or illegal character.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meghan,_Duchess_of_Sussex"}
{"title_page": "Habeas Corpus (1928 film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Habeas Corpus\n| image          = L&H_Habeas_Corpus_1929.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Leo McCarey]]<br>[[James Parrott]]\n| producer       = [[Hal Roach]]\n| writer         = [[Leo McCarey]]<br>[[James Parrott]]<br>[[H. M. Walker]]<ref name=horror>Workman, Christopher; Howarth, Troy (2016). \"Tome of Terror: Horror Films of the Silent Era\". Midnight Marquee Press. p. 324. ISBN 978-1936168-68-2.</ref>\n| starring       = [[Stan Laurel]]<br>[[Oliver Hardy]]<br>[[Richard Carle]]<br>[[Charles A. Bachman]]<br>[[Charley Rogers]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Len Powers]]\n| editing        = [[Richard C. Currier]]\n| distributor    = [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1928|12|1}}\n| runtime        = 20 min.\n| language       = [[Silent film]]<br>English (Original intertitles)\n| budget         = \n| country        = United States\n| Assistant director = [[Lloyd French]]\n| Supervising Director = [[Leo McCarey]]\n}}\n'''''Habeas Corpus''''' is a [[silent film|silent]] [[short film|short subject]] co-directed by [[Leo McCarey]] and [[James Parrott]] starring comedy duo [[Laurel and Hardy]]. It was released by [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] on December 1, 1928\n\n==Plot==\nProfessor Padilla is a mad scientist whose plans have drawn the interest of the police. His latest scheme is to perform a medical experiment on a corpse. Over the supper table, as Professor Padilla is contemplating a new theory that the human brain has a level surface, there's a knock on the door. Stan and Ollie, by chance, happen to arrive at the professor's home in search of a free meal. The professor offers the duo $500 if they will steal a body from a local graveyard. They think the professor is balmy, but they agree to his offer anyway. The conversation is overheard by the professor's butler, Ledoux, who happens to be a police informant.  Ledoux calls police headquarters and is told to go to the graveyard to thwart any theft. Meanwhile the police arrest the mad professor. At the cemetery, Stan and Ollie get into a series of comical misadventures trying to enter the grounds and while digging up a fresh grave. Ledoux manages to slip into the grave while covered in a white sack. Stan and Ollie take Ledoux from the grave. With Ledoux's \"corpse\" slung over Stan's back, Ledoux's legs rip through the bottom of the sack\u2014and he walks step for step behind Stan. Stan and Ollie realize their stolen corpse is still alive and begin to run in panic. The chase ends with Ollie and Ledoux falling into a deep, water-filled hole.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Stan Laurel]] as Stan\n* [[Oliver Hardy]] as Ollie\n* [[Richard Carle]] as Professor Padilla\n* [[Charley Rogers]] as Ledoux\n* [[Charles A. Bachman]] as Detective\n*[[Leo Sulky]] as Detective on telephone\n\n==Production notes==\n''Habeas Corpus'' was filmed in July 16-24 & 30-31 1928.<ref name=randy>[[Randy Skretvedt|Skretvedt, Randy]] (1987). ''Laurel and Hardy: The Magic Behind the Movies''. Beverly Hills, California: Past Times Publishing. {{ISBN|0-940410-29-X}}. p. 130</ref> Although technically a silent film \u2014 having intertitles and no synchronized dialogue \u2014 it was the inaugural Hal Roach film released with a synchronized music and sounds effects track for theatres wired for sound.<ref name=randy/> The Victor sound discs were thought lost until a set surfaced in the 1990s and was reunited with the film elements.<ref>Mitchell, Glenn (1995). ''The Laurel and Hardy Encyclopedia''. London: Batsford Books Ltd. {{ISBN|0-7134-7711-3}}. p. 122</ref>\n\nThe concept of men trolling through a cemetery with a dead body was reworked by [[The Three Stooges]] in their 1945 film ''[[Three Pests in a Mess]]''.<ref>{{cite book| last = Solomon| first = Jon| authorlink = Jon Solomon| coauthors =| title = The Complete Three Stooges: The Official Filmography and Three Stooges Companion| publisher = Comedy III Productions, Inc| date = 2002 | location = | pages = 257| doi =| id = | isbn = 0-9711868-0-4}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nHorror film author Christopher Workman commented, \"One sequence involving the comedy team's attempts to get over the graveyard wall takes up entirely too much running time and mires the proceedings in excessive tedium. Comedic incidents accumulate until the film has reached the requisite running time\".<ref name=horror/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Laurel and Hardy films]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{YouTube|GwyNOuqqNV4|Habeas Corpus, Full Movie}}\n* {{IMDb title|0018970|Habeas Corpus}}\n* {{tcmdb title|614724|Habeas Corpus}}\n* {{Amg movie|149068|Habeas Corpus}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|habeas_corpus|Habeas Corpus}}\n\n{{Laurel and Hardy filmography}}\n{{James Parrott}}\n\n[[Category:1928 films]]\n[[Category:1928 comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American silent short films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by James Parrott]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Leo McCarey]]\n[[Category:Laurel and Hardy (film series)]]\n[[Category:Mad scientist films]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer short films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by H. M. Walker]]\n[[Category:1928 short films]]\n\n\n{{short-silent-comedy-film-stub}}\n[[Category:Comedy short films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Habeas Corpus\n| image          = L&H_Habeas_Corpus_1929.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Leo McCarey]]<br>[[James Parrott]]\n| producer       = [[Hal Roach]]\n| writer         = [[Leo McCarey]]<br>[[James Parrott]]<br>[[H. M. Walker]]<ref name=horror>Workman, Christopher; Howarth, Troy (2016). \"Tome of Terror: Horror Films of the Silent Era\". Midnight Marquee Press. p. 324. ISBN 978-1936168-68-2.</ref>\n| starring       = [[Stan Laurel]]<br>[[Oliver Hardy]]<br>[[Richard Carle]]<br>[[Charles A. Bachman]]<br>[[Charley Rogers]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Len Powers]]\n| editing        = [[Richard C. Currier]]\n| distributor    = [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1928|12|1}}\n| runtime        = 20 min.\n| language       = [[Silent film]]<br>English (Original intertitles)\n| budget         = \n| country        = United States\n| Assistant director = [[Lloyd French]]\n| Supervising Director = [[Leo McCarey]]\n}}\n'''''Habeas Corpus''''' is a [[silent film|silent]] [[short film|short subject]] co-directed by [[Leo McCarey]] and [[James Parrott]] starring comedy duo [[Laurel and Hardy]]. It was released by [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] on December 1, 1928\n\n==Plot==\nProfessor Padilla is a mad scientist whose plans have drawn the interest of the police. His latest scheme is to perform a medical experiment on a corpse. Over the supper table, as Professor Padilla is contemplating a new theory that the human brain has a level surface, there's a knock on the door. Stan and Ollie, by chance, happen to arrive at the professor's home in search of a free meal. The professor offers the duo $500 if they will steal a body from a local graveyard. They think the professor is balmy, but they agree to his offer anyway. The conversation is overheard by the professor's butler, Ledoux, who happens to be a police informant.  Ledoux calls police headquarters and is told to go to the graveyard to thwart any theft. Meanwhile the police arrest the mad professor. At the cemetery, Stan and Ollie get into a series of comical misadventures trying to enter the grounds and while digging up a fresh grave. Ledoux manages to slip into the grave while covered in a white sack. Stan and Ollie take Ledoux from the grave. With Ledoux's \"corpse\" slung over Stan's back, Ledoux's legs rip through the bottom of the sack\u2014and he walks step for step behind Stan. Stan and Ollie realize their stolen corpse is still alive and begin to run in panic. The chase ends with Ollie and Ledoux falling into a deep, water-filled hole.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Stan Laurel]] as Stan\n* [[Oliver Hardy]] as Ollie\n* [[Richard Carle]] as Professor Padilla\n* [[Charley Rogers]] as Ledoux\n* [[Charles A. Bachman]] as Detective\n*[[Leo Sulky]] as Detective on telephone\n\n==Production notes==\n''Habeas Corpus'' was filmed in July 1928.<ref name=randy>[[Randy Skretvedt|Skretvedt, Randy]] (1987). ''Laurel and Hardy: The Magic Behind the Movies''. Beverly Hills, California: Past Times Publishing. {{ISBN|0-940410-29-X}}. p. 130</ref> Although technically a silent film \u2014 having intertitles and no synchronized dialogue \u2014 it was the inaugural Hal Roach film released with a synchronized music and sounds effects track for theatres wired for sound.<ref name=randy/> The Victor sound discs were thought lost until a set surfaced in the 1990s and was reunited with the film elements.<ref>Mitchell, Glenn (1995). ''The Laurel and Hardy Encyclopedia''. London: Batsford Books Ltd. {{ISBN|0-7134-7711-3}}. p. 122</ref>\n\nThe concept of men trolling through a cemetery with a dead body was reworked by [[The Three Stooges]] in their 1945 film ''[[Three Pests in a Mess]]''.<ref>{{cite book| last = Solomon| first = Jon| authorlink = Jon Solomon| coauthors =| title = The Complete Three Stooges: The Official Filmography and Three Stooges Companion| publisher = Comedy III Productions, Inc| date = 2002 | location = | pages = 257| doi =| id = | isbn = 0-9711868-0-4}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nHorror film author Christopher Workman commented, \"One sequence involving the comedy team's attempts to get over the graveyard wall takes up entirely too much running time and mires the proceedings in excessive tedium. Comedic incidents accumulate until the film has reached the requisite running time\".<ref name=horror/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Laurel and Hardy films]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{YouTube|GwyNOuqqNV4|Habeas Corpus, Full Movie}}\n* {{IMDb title|0018970|Habeas Corpus}}\n* {{tcmdb title|614724|Habeas Corpus}}\n* {{Amg movie|149068|Habeas Corpus}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|habeas_corpus|Habeas Corpus}}\n\n{{Laurel and Hardy filmography}}\n{{James Parrott}}\n\n[[Category:1928 films]]\n[[Category:1928 comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American silent short films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by James Parrott]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Leo McCarey]]\n[[Category:Laurel and Hardy (film series)]]\n[[Category:Mad scientist films]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer short films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by H. M. Walker]]\n[[Category:1928 short films]]\n\n\n{{short-silent-comedy-film-stub}}\n[[Category:Comedy short films]]\n", "name_user": "Mugsie Long", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Habeas_Corpus_(1928_film)"}
