n| {{percent and number|1,327|17,246|disp=table|1|pad=yes}}\n| 1,249\n| {{PAGR|color=true|2015.5835|1,327|2010.3315|1,249}}\n| {{convert|16.54|km2|abbr=values|disp=table}}\n| {{convert|{{sigfig|1,327/16.54|2}}|PD/km2|abbr=values|disp=table}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 4\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"border-right:0;background-color:initial;\" | {{coord|20.4158|N|121.9479|E|name=Mahatao|region:PH-BTN_type:city|format=hidden}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-weight:bold;border-left:0;\" colspan=\"2\" | [[Mahatao, Batanes|Mahatao]]\n| {{percent and number|1,555|17,246|disp=table|1|pad=yes}}\n| 1,583\n| {{PAGR|color=true|2015.5835|1,555|2010.3315|1,583}}\n| {{convert|12.90|km2|abbr=values|disp=table}}\n| {{convert|{{sigfig|1,555/12.90|2}}|PD/km2|abbr=values|disp=table}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 4\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"border-right:0;background-color:initial;\" | {{coord|20.3324|N|121.8735|E|name=Sabtang|region:PH-BTN_type:city|format=hidden}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-weight:bold;border-left:0;\" colspan=\"2\" | [[Sabtang, Batanes|Sabtang]]\n| {{percent and number|1,621|17,246|disp=table|1|pad=yes}}\n| 1,637\n| {{PAGR|color=true|2015.5835|1,621|2010.3315|1,637}}\n| {{convert|40.70|km2|abbr=values|disp=table}}\n| {{convert|{{sigfig|1,621/40.70|2}}|PD/km2|abbr=values|disp=table}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 6\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"border-right:0;background-color:initial;\" | {{coord|20.3497|N|121.9394|E|name=Uyugan|region:PH-BTN_type:city|format=hidden}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-weight:bold;border-left:0;\" colspan=\"2\" | [[Uyugan, Batanes|Uyugan]]\n| {{percent and number|1,297|17,246|disp=table|1|pad=yes}}\n| 1,240\n| {{PAGR|color=true|2015.5835|1,297|2010.3315|1,240}}\n| {{convert|16.28|km2|abbr=values|disp=table}}\n| {{convert|{{sigfig|1,297/16.28|2}}|PD/km2|abbr=values|disp=table}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 4\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"border-right:0;\" |\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"border-left:0;text-align:left;font-size:medium;font-variant:small-caps;letter-spacing:0.05em;\" | Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | 17,246\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | 16,604\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | {{PAGR|color=true|2015.5835|17,246|2010.3315|16,604}}\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | 219.01\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | {{convert|219.01|km2|disp=number|2}}\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | {{sigfig|17,246/219.01|2}}\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | {{convert|{{sigfig|17,246/219.01|2}}|PD/km2|disp=number}}\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[List of barangays in Batanes|29]]\n|- class=\"sortbottom\" style=\"background-color:#F2F2F2;line-height:1.3em;border-top:double grey;\"\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"border-width:thin 0 0 thin;\" |\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"border-width:thin 0 0 0;text-align:center;padding:0.7em 0;\" | {{Color box|white|\u2020|border=darkgray}}{{thinsp}}Provincial&nbsp;capital\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"border-width:thin 0 0 0;text-align:left;padding:0.7em 0;\" | {{Color box|white|border=darkgray}}{{thinsp}}Municipality\n|- class=\"sortbottom\" style=\"background-color:#F2F2F2;line-height:1.3em;font-size:110%;\"\n| colspan=\"13\" style=\"border-top:0;text-align:left;padding:0 10.5em;\" |\n{{notelist-lr|refs=\n{{efn-lr|name=Coord|The ''globe''&nbsp;[[File:WMA button2b.png|frameless|upright=0.1]] icon marks the [[town&nbsp;center]].}}\n}}\n|}\n{{col-break}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Barangays===\nThe 6 municipalities of the province comprise a total of 29 [[barangay]]s, with ''Ihuvok II'' in [[Basco, Batanes|Basco]] as the most populous in 2010, and ''Nakanmuan'' in [[Sabtang, Batanes|Sabtang]] as the least.{{PH census|2010|02}}\n{{Further|List of barangays in Batanes}}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Philippine Census\n| title    = Population Census<br/>of Batanes\n| 1990     = 15026\n| 1995     = 14180\n| 2000     = 16467\n| 2007     = 15974\n| 2010     = 16604\n| 2015     = 17246\n| footnote = Source: Philippine Statistics Authority{{PH census|2015|02}}{{PH census|2010|02}}{{PH census|2010}}\n}}\n\nThe population of Batanes in the {{PH wikidata|population_as_of}} was {{PH wikidata|population_total}} people,{{PH census|current|02}} with a density of {{convert|{{sigfig|{{PH wikidata|population_total}}/{{PH wikidata|area}}|2}}|PD/km2|disp=or}}.\n\n[[File:Ivatan Woman Inside.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.8|An elderly Ivatan woman inside her house.]]\n\nThe natives are called [[Ivatan people|Ivatans]] and share prehistoric cultural and linguistic commonalities with the [[Babuyan]] on [[Babuyan Island]] and the [[Tao people]] of [[Orchid Island]].\n\nThis divided homeland is a result of the [[Dutch people|Dutch]] invasion of [[Taiwan]] in 1624 ([[Dutch Formosa]]) and Spanish invasion in 1626 ([[Spanish Formosa]]). The northern half of the Ivatan homeland, [[Taiwan|Formosa]] and Orchid Island which were formally part of the [[New Spain|Viceroyalty of New Spain]], fell to the Dutch who were in turn expelled in 1662 by forces of the Chinese [[Southern Ming]] dynasty, led by the Chinese pirate [[Koxinga]] who then set himself up as The [[Kingdom of Tungning|King of Taiwan]].\n\nThe southern half of the Ivatan homeland, the islands of Batanes, was reinforced and fortified by Spanish refugees from Formosa before being formally joined in the 18th century with the Spanish government in Manila.\n\nThe main languages spoken in Batanes are [[Ivatan language|Ivatan]], which is spoken on the islands of Batan and Sabtang; [[Itbayaten]], which is spoken primarily on the island of Itbayat. The Ivatan which is dominant in the province is considered to be one of the [[Austronesian languages]]. From college level down to elementary level, the language is widely spoken.<ref>[http://www.batanesonline.com/LiteraryArts/IvatanLanguage.htm www.BatanesOnline.com<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071212194455/http://www.batanesonline.com/LiteraryArts/IvatanLanguage.htm |date=2007-12-12 }}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\nThe large majority (94%) of the island's people adhere to [[Roman Catholicism in the Philippines|Roman Catholicism]]. The remaining faiths are other Christian Churches.\n\n==Ecology==\n[[File:Goats in Batanes.png|thumb|Livestock freely roaming in the green hills in Batanes]]\n\nAn extensive survey of the [[ecology]] of Batanes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.quantum-conservation.org/BatanesSurvey20082.htm|title=Final Report Batanes Biodiversity Survey<!-- Bot generated title -->|website=quantum-conservation.org|accessdate=31 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113171159/http://www.quantum-conservation.org/BatanesSurvey20082.htm|archive-date=13 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> provided the scientific basis for confirming the need for a national park in Batanes protecting the Batanes protected landscapes and seascapes, proposed as a [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]], submitted on 15 August 1993. An effort is underway to declare the whole province, along with the sugar central sites in Negros, as a UNESCO World Heritage Site by the end of 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/?pattern=philippines|title=UNESCO World Heritage Centre - Tentative Lists|first=UNESCO World Heritage|last=Centre|date=|website=whc.unesco.org|accessdate=31 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Flora and fauna===\nThe province is the home of the unique [[conifer]] species ''[[Podocarpus costalis]]''. Although it is reportedly growing in some other places such as coasts of [[Luzon]], [[Catanduanes]] and even [[Taiwan]], full blossoming and fruiting are observed only in Batanes. Its fruiting capacity on the island remains a mystery but is likely due to several factors such as climate, soil and type of substratum of the island.\n\nSeveral species of birds, bats, reptiles and amphibians also inhabit the island; many of those are [[endemic]] to the Philippines. The island is also a sanctuary of different [[bird migration|migratory bird]]s during winter in the [[Northern Hemisphere]].\n\n==Economy==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=August 2017}}\nAbout 75% of the [[Ivatan people|Ivatans]] are farmers and fishermen. The rest are employed in the government and services sector. Garlic and cattle are major cash crops. Ivatans also plant ''camote'' (sweet potato), cassava, ''gabi'' or tuber and a unique variety of white uvi. Sugarcane is raised to produce ''palek'', a kind of native wine, and vinegar.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn recent years, fish catch has declined due to the absence of technical know-how. Employment opportunities are scarce. Most of the educated Ivatans have migrated to urban centers or have gone abroad.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nA [[Wind-Diesel Hybrid Power Systems|wind diesel]] generating plant was commissioned in 2004.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nDistance and bad weather work against its economic growth. Certain commodities like rice, soft drinks, and gasoline carry a 75% to 100% mark-up over Manila retail prices.{{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==Transportation==\nThe island province of Batanes is accessible by air via the [[Basco Airport]] and [[Itbayat Airport]]. There are 3 flights per week from [[Manila]] by SkyJetAir, and from [[Tuguegarao]] (Cagayan) by small local airliners (as of January 2013). [[PAL Express]] flies to Batanes every Monday, Wednesday, and Friday since May 1, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2013/02/airphil-express-to-launch-manila-batanes-flights-on-may.html|title=Airphil Express flies Manila to Basco (Batanes) starting May 2013|author=|date=|website=pinoyadventurista.com|accessdate=31 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Values==\nThe Ivatan people of Batanes are one of the most [[egalitarian]] societies in the Philippines. The prime motivator of the cultural values of the Ivatans are imbibed in their pre-colonial belief systems of respecting [[nature]] and all people. The Ivatans, both the older and younger generations, have one of the highest incidences of social acceptance to minority groups in the country. The Ivatans also have a high respect for the elderly and the prowess of natural phenomena such as waves, sea breeze, lightning, thunders, earthquakes, and wildlife congregations. Discriminating someone based on skin color, ethnic origin, sexual orientation, gender identity, age, and traditions on nature is unacceptable in Ivatan values. [[Land grabbing]] is also a grave crime in Ivatan societies, making ancestral domain certification an important part of Ivatan jurisprudence since the enactment of the IPRA Law. {{citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==Heritage==\n{{Specific section|date=June 2016}}\n\n===Natural===\n[[File:Sabtang Island, Batanes.JPG|thumb|right|White sand beach at [[Sabtang, Batanes|Sabtang]] island]]\n* ''[[Sabtang Island]]'' is undisturbed and unspoiled. It has intermittent white sand beaches with steep mountains and deep canyons with small level areas sporadically found along the coastline. Southwest of Batan Island, Sabtang is accessible by 30-minute falowa ride from Radiwan Port in Ivana. Sabtang Island is also the take off point for [[Ivuhos]] Island from Barangay Nakanmuan.\n* ''[[Itbayat Island]]'' is located north of Batan Island. Itbayat is shaped like a giant bowl. The island is surrounded by massive boulders and cliffs rising from {{convert|20|to(-)|70|ft|m|abbr=off}} [[above sea level]] and has no shoreline. It has a dirt airstrip for light aircraft. A regular ferry runs the Batan-Itbayat route. Travel time is about four hours by falowa from Basco Seaport. A light plane flies from Basco Airport to Itbayat at around P1,875 per person and leaves only when the plane is full.\n* ''[[Batan Island]]'' is the most populated island of the province. It is composed of four municipalities: [[Basco, Batanes|Basco]], Ivana, Uyugan and Mahatao. Basco is the center of commerce and seat of the provincial government.\n* ''[[Mount Iraya]]'' is a dormant volcano standing at {{convert|1,517|m|ft|abbr=off}} whose last eruption was recorded in 505 AD. Mountaineering, trekking and trailblazing are recommended sports activities on the mountain. Walking distance from Basco, the top of Mt. Iraya can be reached in about three hours.\n* ''[[Mavulis Island]]'' is the northernmost island of Batanes. From this location, one can see Formosa (Taiwan) on a clear day. Tatus or coconut crabs abound in the island surrounded by rich marine life.\n* ''Di-atay Beach'' is a cove with multi-colored rocks and white sand ideal for picnics and beach combing. Located along the highway of Mahatao, it is {{convert|9.85|km|mi|2|abbr=off}} from Basco.\n* ''Songsong'' in Chadpidan Bay is an hour of exhilarating trek from Basco proper ({{convert|3|km|mi|abbr=off}}). It is famous for its beautiful sunset view.\n* ''Naidi Hills'' is walking distance from Basco.\n* ''Chawa Cave'' is for the more adventurous. An enchanted cave with a natural salt bed whose mouth opens to the south China Sea and is accessible through the boulders of Chawa Point in Mahatao. It is {{convert|4|km|abbr=off}} from Basco.\n* Sitio Diura at Racuj-a-Ide is the fishermens village at Mananoy Bay. Fishing season is marked by a festival in mid-March called Kapayvanuvanua. Visitors are treated with fresh fish delicacies from the Pacific Ocean. Within the area is the legendary Spring of Youth and living cave with crystal limestone formations. The bay is {{convert|9|km|mi|spell=in|abbr=off}} from Basco.\n* ''Nakabuang Cave'' is {{convert|5.5|km|mi|1|abbr=off}} from San Vicente Centro in Sabtang.\n* ''Mt. Matarem'' is an extinct volcano {{convert|495|m|ft|abbr=off}} at its summit. It is {{convert|8|km|mi|spell=in|abbr=off}} from Basco.\n* ''White Beach'' at Vatang, Hapnit and Mavatuy Point, all in Mahatao.\n* ''Storm-proof'' Stone houses in Batanes many residents during typhoon made up their already-fortified houses with wood and secured the roofs with nets and ropes. This was done to ensure that the structures\u2014which symbolize the Ivatan's strength and resilience against disasters\u2014outlast the high-pressure winds of typhoon that is expected to unleash. Tapangkos or covering were also installed on the doors and windows of several buildings in Batanes, including the capitol building. During heavy storms it was also a time for bayanihan of the residents as they helped each other tie down roofs.\n\n===Manmade===\n\n* ''Radar Tukon'' was a United States weather station on a hilltop. It offers a magnificent 360-degree view of Batan Island, the South China Sea, Mt. Iraya, Basco proper, boulder lined cliffs and the Pacific Ocean. At present, it houses the northernmost weather station in the Philippines, the Basco Radar Station, and is only {{convert|2.75|km|mi|2|abbr=off}} from Basco.\n* ''Old Loran Station'' housed a US Coast Guard detachment for almost two decades and is about {{convert|25|km|mi|0|abbr=off}} from Basco.\n* ''Ruins Of Songsong'' is a ghost barangay which is a cluster of roofless shells of old stone houses abandoned after a tidal wave that hit the island of Batan in the 1950s. It has a long stretch of beach. The ruins are {{convert|23|km|mi|0|abbr=off}} from Basco.\n* ''San Jose Church'' in Ivana was built in 1814. It has a crenelated fortress-like campanile. The church fronts the Ivana Seaport and is {{convert|14|km|mi|abbr=off}} from Basco.\n* ''Kanyuyan Beach & Port'' at Baluarte Bay in Basco is the port of call of the cargo ships bringing goods from Manila.\n* ''San Carlos Borromeo Church'' and a convent at Mahatao are {{convert|6|km|mi|spell=in|abbr=off}} from Basco. It was completed in 1789 and still retains its centuries-old features.\n* ''Idjang''s or fortified stone fortresses where the native Ivatans' ancestors migrated to Batanes as early as 4,000 BC lived in them for defensive cover.\n* ''Fundacion Pacita'' is a lodging house and restaurant, which was formerly owned by [[Pacita Abad]], the most iconic Ivatan visual artist. The house has been redecorated and filled with numerous art works of Pacita Abad after she died in 2004.\n\n===Historical===\n\n* ''Radiwan Point'' at Ivana Seaport is where the Katipuneros landed in September 18, 1898. It is also the ferry station of the falowas plying the islands of Sabtang and Itbayat.\n* Boat-shaped Stone Grave Markers, Chuhangin Burial Site, Ivuhos Island, Sabtang, Batanes\n* Chavulan Burial Jar Site, Ivuhos Island, Sabtang Island\n* Arrangement of Stone with Holes, Sumnanga, Sabtang\n* Columnar Stones, Post Holes, Stone Anchors, Itbud Idyang, Uyugan, Batanes\n* Arrangement of Stone Walls, Idyang Site, Basco, Batanes\n* Paso Stone Formation, Ivuhos Island, Sabtang, Batanes\n* Columnar Stone with Holes, Mahatao, Batanes\n\n===Intangible Heritage===\nIn 2012, the [[National Commission for Culture and the Arts]] (NCCA) and the ICHCAP of [[UNESCO]] published ''Pinagmulan: Enumeration from the Philippine Inventory of Intangible Cultural Heritage''. The first edition of the [[UNESCO]]-backed book included (1) ''Laji'', (2) ''Kapayvanuvanuwa Fishing Ritual'', (3) ''Kapangdeng Ritual'', (4) ''Traditional Boats in Batanes'', (5) ''Sinadumparan Ivatan House Types'', (6) ''Ivatan Basketry'', and (7) ''Ivatan (Salakot) Hat Weaving'', signifying their great importance to Philippine intangible cultural heritage. The local government of Batanes, in cooperation with the NCCA, is given the right to nominate the 7 distinct elements into the [[UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage Lists]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ichcap.org/eng/ek/sub3/sub2.php|title=ICHCAP - e-Knowledge Center|author=|date=|website=www.ichcap.org|accessdate=31 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Image gallery==\n<gallery mode=packed heights=130px>\nFile:Old Spanish Bridge.png|An old [[Spain|Spanish]] bridge in [[Ivana, Batanes|Ivana]]\nFile:Valuga Beach.png|A rocky shore in Batanes\nFile:Gloomy Sky Over the Lighthouse.png|Gloomy sky over the lighthouse in Basco\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links=