 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:Solicitors General for England and Wales]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Staffordshire University]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:English Roman Catholics]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Mike O'Brien}}\n{{More footnotes|date=January 2010}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Mike O'Brien\n| honorific-suffix = [[Queen's Counsel|QC]]<!-- Do not insert 'PC' for Privy Council. This is reserved only for peers -->\n| image = Mike O'Brien 2.jpg\n| office = [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Health Services]]\n| term_start = 8 June 2009\n| term_end = 11 May 2010\n| predecessor = [[Ben Bradshaw]]\n| successor = [[Simon Burns]]\n| primeminister = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| office2 = [[Department of Energy and Climate Change|Minister of State for Energy]]\n| term_start2 = 5 October 2008\n| term_end2 = 8 June 2009\n| predecessor2 = [[Department of Energy and Climate Change|Office Created]]\n| successor2 = [[Joan Ruddock]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| office3 = [[Department for Work and Pensions|Minister of State for Pensions]]\n| term_start3 = 27 June 2007\n| term_end3 = 5 October 2008\n| primeminister3 = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| predecessor3 = [[James Purnell]]\n| successor3 = [[Rosie Winterton]]\n| office4 = [[Solicitor General for England and Wales]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| predecessor4 = [[Harriet Harman]]\n| successor4 = [[Vera Baird]]\n| term_start4 = 11 May 2005\n| term_end4 = 27 June 2007\n| office5 = [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Trade and Industry]]\n| primeminister5 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| predecessor5 = [[Nigel Griffiths]]\n| successor5 = [[Ian McCartney]]\n| term_start5 = 10 September 2004\n| term_end5 = 11 May 2005\n| office6 = [[Minister of State for Trade]]\n| primeminister6 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| predecessor6 = [[Elizabeth Symons, Baroness Symons of Vernham Dean|Elizabeth Symons]]\n| successor6 = [[Douglas Alexander]]\n| term_start6 = 13 June 2003\n| term_end6 = 10 September 2004\n| office7 = [[Under-Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs]]\n| primeminister7 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| predecessor7 = [[Ben Bradshaw]]\n| successor7 = [[Chris Mullin (politician)|Chris Mullin]]\n| term_start7 = 29 May 2002\n| term_end7 = 13 June 2003\n| office8 = [[Minister of State for Immigration|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Immigration]]\n| primeminister8 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| predecessor8 = [[Emily Blatch, Baroness Blatch|The Baroness Blatch]]\n| successor8 = [[Barbara Roche]]\n| term_start8 = 2 May 1997\n| term_end8 = 8 June 2001\n| office9 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[North Warwickshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Warwickshire]]\n| majority9 = 7,553 (16.1%)\n| predecessor9 = [[Francis Maude]]\n| successor9 = [[Daniel Byles]]\n| term_start9 = 9 April 1992\n| term_end9 = 12 April 2010\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1954|6|19|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Worcester]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[British people|British]]\n| spouse = Alison Joy Munro\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| alma_mater = [[North Staffordshire Polytechnic]]\n| religion = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| website = [http://www.mikeobrien.org.uk Official site]\n}}\n\n'''Michael O'Brien''' [[Queen's Counsel|QC]] (born 19 June 1954) is a [[British people|British]] lawyer and former [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician who was the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[North Warwickshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Warwickshire]] from [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]] to [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]], serving in a number of cabinet posts.<ref name=twfy>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/mike_o'brien/north_warwickshire|title=Mike O'Brien Former Labour MP for North Warwickshire|publisher=Theyworkforyou.com|accessdate=10 January 2011}}</ref> In the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|May 2010 general election]], he lost his [[North Warwickshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Warwickshire]] constituency to [[Dan Byles]], the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party candidate]] by 54 votes. O'Brien was re-selected as Labour's candidate in North Warwickshire for the 2015 general election in June 2013,<ref name=ryan>{{cite news|url=http://www.nuneaton-news.co.uk/News/Mike-OBrien-to-take-on-Dan-Byles-20130611084102.htm|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130708123834/http://www.nuneaton-news.co.uk/News/Mike-OBrien-to-take-on-Dan-Byles-20130611084102.htm|url-status=dead|archivedate=8 July 2013|title=Mike O'Brien to take on Dan Byles|author=Ryan Merriman|work=Nuneaton News|date=11 June 2013|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref> but lost to the Conservative Party candidate [[Craig Tracey]].\n\n==Early life==\nMike O'Brien attended state schools, a Roman Catholic primary school, St George's <ref>http://www.st-georgescatholic.co.uk</ref> and then later [[Blessed Edward Oldcorne School]] ([[Worcester]]). He studied for a BA in History and Politics at [[Staffordshire University|North Staffordshire Polytechnic]], then gained a [[Postgraduate Certificate in Education|PGCE]]. From 1977\u201380, he was a trainee solicitor, then trained as a teacher from 1980\u20131. He lectured in Business Law at [[Colchester Sixth Form College|Colchester College of Further and Higher Education]] from 1981\u201387. From 1987\u201392, he practised as a solicitor specialising in criminal law including handling cases of murder and City fraud and acted for a major defendant in the [[Knightsbridge Security Deposit robbery]].<ref name=no5C>{{cite web|url=http://www.no5.com/cms/documents/Mike%20O'Brien(1).pdf |title=No5 Chambers:Mike O'Brien:Crime |work=www.no5.com |accessdate=8 July 2013 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He became a Queen's Counsel in 2007.<ref name=no5APL>{{cite web|url=http://www.no5.com/barristers/barrister-cvs/mike-obrien--administrative-public-law/|title=Mike O'Brien \u2013 Administrative & Public Law|work=www.no5.com|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref> He now practices as a barrister at No5 Chambers in Birmingham.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.no5.com/people/barristers/mike-obrien/|title=No5 Barristers Chambers|website=www.no5.com|accessdate=18 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nO'Brien contested [[Ruislip-Northwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Ruislip Northwood]] in 1983, and North Warwickshire in 1987.\nHe was elected as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for the West Midlands constituency of [[North Warwickshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Warwickshire]] at the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]], defeating the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] incumbent [[Francis Maude]], and lost his seat to the Conservative candidate at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]].\n\nHe served on the Home Affairs Select Committee from November 1992 to May 1993 focusing on reports on Youth Justice and the defence of provocation in murder cases involving a spouse.\n\nHe was a member of the Home Affairs Select Committee which opened up scrutiny of the intelligence services by Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199899/cmselect/cmhaff/291/29103.htm|title=House of Commons - Home Affairs - Third Report|website=publications.parliament.uk|accessdate=18 May 2019}}</ref> This led to the first meeting of MPs and the head of MI5, then Stella Remington, and this later led to wider parliamentary scrutiny of the intelligence services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/westminster-six-taste-the-secret-life-at-mi5s-table-steve-boggan-turns-sleuth-at-the-spycatchers-hq-1479368.html|title=Westminster Six taste the secret life at MI5's table: Steve Boggan|date=19 January 1993|work=The Independent|accessdate=18 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Home Affairs Committee also did a report on Domestic Violence, which focused on the extent of the problem. One of the strongest recommendations of the report was: \"The first priority for government action on domestic violence should be the establishment of a central, co-ordinated policy for refuge provision throughout the country. We believe that this could well be the single greatest cost-saving measure that could be taken\". This led to an expansion in the number of refugees in the following decade.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/debates/?id=1993-07-21a.372.0|title=I want first to congratulate the...: 21 Jul 1993: House of Commons debates|website=TheyWorkForYou|accessdate=18 May 2019}}</ref> The report also focused on the effect of immigration law on victims of domestic violence and has been credited with supporting a feminist perspective on domestic violence. Influenced by evidence from Southall Black Sisters the report also raised awareness of the problems of domestic servants who faced deportation if they complained about being abused and this later led to changes in the immigration rules when Mike O\u2019Brien became Immigration Minister.<ref>Home Truths About Domestic Violence: Feminist Influences on Policy and Practice - A Reader Jalna Hanmwer Catherine Itzin</ref>\n\nMike O'Brien introduced a Private Members Bill on 21 April 1993, the Criminal Justice Amendment (No.2) Bill, to allow previous convictions to be taken into account when sentencing a convicted person. This sought to amend the Criminal Justice Act 1991. The Government then accepted the principle and later amended the law.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/commons/1993/apr/21/criminal-justice-amendment-no-2#S6CV0223P0_19930421_HOC_151|title=Criminal Justice (Amendment) (No. 2) (Hansard, 21 April 1993)|website=api.parliament.uk|accessdate=18 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1993 he became the first Labour Parliamentary Adviser to the Police Federation of England and Wales in 20 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-mp-to-advise-police-1467899.html|title=Labour MP to advise police|date=17 December 1993|work=The Independent|accessdate=18 May 2019}}</ref> He opposed cuts in Police Funding, criticising the then Home Secretary Michael Howard saying, \u201cI am appalled at how badly the Home Secretary \u2026has handicapped the police and the fight against crime.\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/police-warn-howard-over-job-cuts-fears-of-privatisation-and-46000-fewer-officers-in-force-1469542.html|title=Police warn Howard over job cuts: Fears of privatisation and 46,000|date=28 December 1993|work=The Independent|accessdate=18 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/debates/?id=1996-01-30a.904.1|title=The House will know that for the...: 30 Jan 1996: House of Commons debates|website=TheyWorkForYou|accessdate=18 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nMike O'Brien subsequently transferred to the Treasury Select Committee where he worked on a report into the collapse of Barings Bank and other reports on City Fraud and Independence of the Bank of England<ref>First Report, Barings Bank and International Regulation, HC (Session 1996-97) 65.  TCSC 18 November 1996 HC 65</ref>\n\nHe clashed with Sir Robin Butler when the Treasury Select Committee investigated the impartiality of the civil service. He criticised the cabinet secretary for allowing himself to be used to investigate whether a Minister Secretary Jonathan Aitken had stayed at a Paris Hotel. \u201cSir Robin was, at best, ill qualified to undertake any such investigation, as he did not in any previous incarnation have experience of being a policeman, a private investigator or a barrister trained in interrogation. He had none of the qualifications for playing the detective\u2026 Sir Robin Butler should not allow himself to be dragged into the gutter of partisan politics, nor should any civil servant. Some members of the Select Committee fear that impartiality has been undermined, and that should never happen again.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199495/cmhansrd/1995-03-23/Debate-16.html|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 23 Mar 1995|website=publications.parliament.uk|accessdate=18 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nMike O'Brien raised concerns in Parliament after the Matrix Churchill manufacturing plant in Coventry closed, calling on the government to \u201censure that those workers and their families are compensated for the loss of their livelihood\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199394/cmhansrd/1994-10-31/Orals-2.htm|title=Page cannot be found|website=UK Parliament|accessdate=18 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs a member of Treasury Select Committee he called for the Director of the Serious Fraud Office \u201cto go\u201d and for an inquiry into the case of Roger Levitt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/commons/1995/jul/17/roger-levitt-case|title=Roger Levitt Case (Hansard, 17 July 1995)|website=api.parliament.uk|accessdate=18 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Minister of State for Immigration===\nMike O\u2019Brien served as Parliamentary Under Secretary  Minister of State for Immigration in the Home Office from 1997 till May 1999. \nMike O'Brien, said that the last Conservative government left the immigration system in \"''a complete shambles''\" and it could take two years or more to process an application for asylum <ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/174185.stm|title= UK &#124; Immigration service 'grinding to a halt'|work=BBC News|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> and \u201c''we need to speed up the system. The deportation system is manifestly slow and cumbersome and produces inequity''.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199495/cmhansrd/1995-03-23/Debate-16.html|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 23 Mar 1995|website=publications.parliament.uk|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nO\u2019Brien described to a colleague the chaos he discovered in the department on being appointed as Immigration Minister: \u201cOnce, on a visit to IND, he opened a cupboard and found it full of unanswered mail, having just been assured there were no more outstanding letters.  A hapless junior official was summoned. His explanation? \u2018We put them there so that the Minister wouldn\u2019t see them\u2019\u201d.<ref>Chris Mullin \u201cView from the Foothills\u201d Profile Books Ltd 2009. Page 264</ref>\n\nIn October 1997, after consulting with lawyers from Stonewall, Mike O\u2019Brien announced a change in UK immigration law allowing citizens to sponsor unmarried partners in 1997, including same-sex couples in this group. \"''Under this concession, a couple must show that they have been living together for four years or more and intend to continue to live together permanently. Once admitted they will have to show that the relationship has subsisted for a further year before being granted settlement''\". In 1999, again consulting with Stonewall, he announced this was improved by reducing the required length of relationship to two years. This was the first step taken by the New Labour government toward equality for the LGTBQ community.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmselect/cmhaff/775/775we39.htm|title=House of Commons - Home Affairs - Written Evidence|website=publications.parliament.uk|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/231961159|title=Citizenship and Same Sex Relationships|website=ResearchGate|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs a Home Office Minister responsible for race relations, Mike O\u2019Brien worked with Jack Straw to set up the Stephen Lawrence Inquiry, meeting with the Lawrence family and their lawyers. He later endorsed the Macpherson Report in a book called \u201cInstitutional Racism and the Police: Fact or Fiction?\u201d saying that, ''\u201cThe Report is about securing the commitment of all of us to tackling racism, whether open or unwitting throughout our society, not just in the police force.... The important thing for all of us is that Britain is a multiracial society. We have a choice whether to succeed as one or not. Racism in all its guises endangers and undermines the future success of our society; that is why to be racist in today\u2019s multi-racial Britain is to be \u2018un-British\u2019.''\u201d <ref>\u201cInstitutional Racism and the Police: Fact or Fiction?\u201d David G. Green (Editor) John G.D. Grieve & Julie French, Michael Ignatieff, Mike O\u2019Brien, Robert Skidelsky. Institute for the Study of Civil Society London First published August 2000 \u00a9 The Institute for the Study of Civil Society 2000 email: books@civil-society.org.uk Pages 25-26</ref>\n\nSince 1992, the trend for net migration to the UK had been rising and continued till 1999. In 1997, annual net immigration stood at 56,000 but by 2001 net immigration had risen to 191,500.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/npp/national-population-projections/2010-based-reference-volume--series-pp2/migration.html |title=ONS Migration statistics |publisher=Office for National Statistic |date=March 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn March 1998, Mike O\u2019Brien told Parliament that in 1994, the previous administration had scrapped the \u201cembarkation checks for passengers travelling from ferry ports and small ports to destinations within the European Union; so, for four years, 40 per cent. of departing passengers have not been seen by an immigration officer\u2026We inherited an embarkation control which serves little purpose in the tracking down of immigration offenders\u201d and therefore  Mike O'Brien described the procedure of checking passports as \"routine and unproductive\" and said that \u201cEnhanced technology, such as closed circuit television, combined with close liaison between the border agencies, port operators and airlines, will create a stronger deterrent than the current immigration departure checks.\u201d<ref name=\"auto\">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/264140/287.pdf</ref> The [[Immigration Service Union]] criticised the move, saying the changes made it harder to ensure that illegal immigrants ordered out of the country actually left.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/66236.stm |title=Journey's end for passport checks |publisher=BBC News |date=March 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1998, Mike O'Brien announced that inhabitants of the island of [[Montserrat]], which had been hit by volcanic eruptions, were able to stay in Britain indefinitely.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/98364.stm |title=Montserrat volcano evacuees can stay in UK |publisher=BBC News |date=March 2014}}</ref> O'Brien's time as Minister of State for Immigration saw him deal with the late 1990s administrative problems including delays in officials giving clearance to NHS doctors<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/329571.stm |title=Health Immigration delays 'cause NHS chaos'  |publisher=BBC News |date=March 2014}}</ref> and backlogs in processing applications for passports. The delays in issuing passports made national headlines<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/359910.stm |title=Fuming for a passport   |publisher=BBC News |date=March 2014}}</ref> and resulted in the UK Passport Agency being stripped of its Charter Mark for customer service.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/401897.stm |title=Passport office stripped of award   |publisher=BBC News |date=March 2014}}</ref>\n\nMike O'Brien also took through major reforms in the Immigration and Asylum Act, including introducing fines for hauliers found to have illegal migrants in their lorry, whether or not the haulier knew of their presence.<ref>https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199899/cmstand/special/st990420/pm/pt2/90420s01.htm</ref>\n\nResponding to a debate on forced marriage on 10 February 1999, Mike O\u2019Brien told MPs that  \u201c\u2026''multicultural sensitivity is no excuse for official silence or moral blindness. We long ago abolished laws that treated women as chattels. We cannot shelter or tolerate bad practices under the guise of sensitivity''.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/commons/1999/feb/10/human-rights-women#S6CV0325P0_19990|title=Human Rights (Women) (Hansard, 10 February 1999)|website=api.parliament.uk|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref> He announced a national dialogue on how to deal with forced marriage which led the forced marriage unit run jointly by the Foreign Office and the in the Home Office.<ref>https://www.soas.ac.uk/honourcrimes/resources/file55689.pdf</ref>\n\nMike O\u2019Brien developed the procedures for the creation of the Special Immigration Appeals Commission (also known by the acronym SIAC) as a superior court of record in the United Kingdom established by the Special Immigration Appeals Commission Act 1997.  SIAC deals with appeals from persons deported by the Home Secretary for reasons of national security or terrorism. It allows the security service to disclose confidential intelligence information to the court without disclosing its sources. Information and the source is disclosed to a special advocate who acts for the person but cannot disclose the source of information to either the person or their main lawyers.  Speaking at the close of the committee stage of the bill, O\u2019Brien said the law had, \u201cbeen governed by the terms of the European Court of Human Rights judgment in the case of Chahal. It is about creating the right balance between the liberty of the individual and the safety of the state.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199798/cmhansrd/vo971126/debtext/71126-37.htm|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 26 Nov 1997 (pt 37)|website=publications.parliament.uk|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Hinduja affair====\nWhilst serving as Minister of State for Immigration, O'Brien had to deal with the [[Hinduja affair#2001 Hinduja affair|2001 Hinduja affair]]. His testimony that Peter Mandelson had telephoned him on behalf of [[S P Hinduja]], who was at the time seeking British citizenship, led to Mandelson's resignation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/1134819.stm |title=BBC News &#124; SOUTH ASIA &#124; Mandelson resigns over Hinduja affair |publisher=News.bbc.co.uk |date= 24 January 2001<!--, 14:30 GMT -->|accessdate=3 October 2008}}</ref> An independent enquiry by Sir Anthony Hammond came to the conclusion that Mike O'Brien had acted correctly and neither Mandelson nor anyone else had acted improperly.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Minister for Constitutional Affairs===\nOn 10 May 1999, Mike O\u2019Brien became the Minister for Constitutional Affairs, taking through the Commons the Freedom of Information Act, The Political Parties, Elections and Referendums Act 2000, two Representation of the People Acts and introduced a White Paper on Alcohol Licensing Reform.\n\nAs the Minister responsible for Race Relations, he developed the Race Relations (Amendment) Act 2000 which placed obligations on all public bodies to promote good race relations. He also worked to develop closer links between the Government and the Muslim community, something he continued to work on over the next decade, particularly after 9/11.<ref>https://www.wiltonpark.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/wp826-programme.pdf</ref>\n\nHe regularly spoke at Muslim community events and as the Minister for Race Relations in the Home Office he was responsible for building a dialogue between Muslim Groups and the Home Office. Later after becoming a Foreign office Minister and in the aftermath of 9/11, \u201cthe FCO, led by Mike O\u2019Brien, try to strengthen its relationship with the British Muslim community\u201d and this included sponsoring the British Haj delegation.<ref>Greene, Toby (2013). Blair, Labour, and Palestine: Conflicting Views on Middle East Peace After 9/11. Pg154 Bloomsbury 3PL.. {{ISBN|978-1441143723}}</ref>\n \nAt a ministerial meeting, O\u2019Brien joined Chris Mullin in warning the Prime Minister that his education reforms were \u201chectoring\u201d teachers.<ref>Chris Mullin \u201cA View from the Foothills\u201d Profile Books Ltd 2009 Page 50</ref>\n\nMike O\u2019Brien changed the rules so that cosmetics could not be tested on animals, but considered resigning after the Home Secretary refused to have an inquiry into animal rights complaints about Huntingdon Life Sciences.<ref>Chris Mullin \u201cView from the Foothills\u201d Profile Books Ltd 2009. Page 142</ref>\n \nIn July 2000, Mike O'Brien became a \u201chave a go hero\u201d after he intercepted an alleged shoplifter being chased by a security guard, by sticking his leg out to trip him up as he ran past. Although the man ran off after a scuffle, he had dropped his car keys when he fell and police traced and arrested him. Mike O\u2019Brien had broken his leg, but despite this went straight on to conduct a television interview.<ref>http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/824277.stm</ref> He was on crutches for six weeks. He said, \"It is something anyone would have done\u2026they caught the man\u2026 so I was able to have some small sense of satisfaction.\"<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2000/jul/08/rebeccaallison</ref>\n\nOn 21 December 2000 in the Deregulation (Sunday Dancing) Order 2000, Mike O'Brien ended the ban on any public dancing on a Sunday which had existed since the Sunday Observance Act 1780. He faced opposition to the move from the then Conservative MPs Theresa May and Philip Hammond.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/09/01/theresa-may-voted-against-scrapping-a-law-which-would-have-banne/</ref><ref>http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2000/3372/made</ref> Scrapping the ban, O\u2019Brien said: \u201c''Our proposals will give freedom of choice for people as well as remove an unnecessary regulation on business. Be it line dancing, square dancing, ballroom or disco, it is plainly daft to have a ban on dancing because it is a Sunday.''\u201d<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/>\n\nIn 2001 when the Government proposed to introduce ID cards, O\u2019Brien wrote a pamphlet for \u201cLiberty\u201d attacking ID cards saying, \u201cIdentity cards were abolished in the early fifties for good reasons. They were unreliable in proving identity and damaged the relationship between the public and the police. When it comes to fighting terrorism and serious crime, there are more effective things to spend our money on\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.libertyhumanrights.org.uk/news/press-releases/former-minister-id-cards-dont-work|title=Former Minister: ID cards don't work|date=1 October 2001|publisher=Liberty Human Rights|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Minister for the Middle East===\nAt the [[Foreign Office]] from 2002 to 2003 he was Minister for the Middle East. He went to Libya to hold the first meeting of a British Minister with Libyan leader [[Colonel Gaddafi]] which opened the way to better relations between Gadaffi's Libya and the West and helped lead to cooperation on ending controversial Libyan weapons research programmes.<ref>https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/taming-a-tyrant-nxpk25x3tp7</ref>\n\nIn the run up to the [[2003 Iraq War]], he addressed parliament stating the Governments position saying \"''The body of evidence that Saddam Hussein possesses a fearsome range of weapons of mass destruction is substantial. The evidence comes from the UN reports, from Dr Blix, from our own intelligence and indeed from Saddam Hussein himself, who last night, oddly, admitted that the Iraqis had found a biological bomb and wanted to show us. Let us be clear: Saddam Hussein has weapons of mass destruction and he is a threat to his people, his neighbours and ultimately the middle east and the wider world.''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030226/debtext/30226-33.htm|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 26 Feb 2003 (pt 33)|first=Department of the Official Report (Hansard), House of Commons|last=Westminster|website=www.publications.parliament.uk|accessdate=20 June 2017}}</ref> ''The UN Security Council is in no doubt about that. That is why its resolution 1441 gave Saddam Hussein a final opportunity to comply with a string of legally binding obligations imposed on him over the past 12 years. Nearly four months later, Saddam Hussein has not taken that final opportunity. I cannot put the matter more crisply than Dr. Blix. He has reported that Iraq ''\"''appears not to have come to a genuine acceptance . . . of the disarmament which was demanded of it\"''. Before adding \"''If we have to undertake military action and American and British troops are committed and have to go into Baghdad, I suspect that the Iraqi people will be the first to cheer.''\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030226/debtext/30226-34.htm|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 26 Feb 2003 (pt 34)|first=Department of the Official Report (Hansard), House of Commons|last=Westminster|website=www.publications.parliament.uk|accessdate=20 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nChris Mullin says that privately when Mullin asked for advice about what to say to Blair at an NEC meeting Mike O\u2019Brien said, \u201cTell him not to make any more promises to George Bush. Somewhere along the line he\u2019s promised Bush that we will be there with him and now he can\u2019t back down because his integrity is at stake\u201d.<ref>Chris Mullin \u201cView from the foothills.\u201d Profile Books Ltd 2009 Page 384</ref>\n\nIn May 2003, Chris Mullin says Mike O\u2019Brien intended to resign as a Foreign Office Minister over Iraq, \u201cBecause I don\u2019t believe what I am being asked to say about the existence of weapons of mass destruction. The Security Service is still saying they will be found, but I don\u2019t believe them.\u201d Mullin, who opposed the war, convinced him to \u201cstay put\u201d because it was unnecessary \u201cself immolation\u201d to resign.<ref>Chris Mullin \u201cView from the foothills\u201d Profile Books Ltd 2009. Page 408</ref> Mike O\u2019Brien was not criticised in the various reports into the Iraq war.\n\nHe was the first Western Minister into Baghdad after the Iraq War and worked on relationships with Iran, Syria and Afghanistan during this period.{{citation needed|date=March 2014}}\n\nO\u2019Brien was sent by Tony Blair to meet President Assad in Damascus to secure the release of two SAS soldiers picked up by Syrian security crossing the border and was credited with the success.<ref>https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/two-sbs-survive-ambush-desert-trek-and-syria-jail-q6rls3lvpwm</ref>\n\nMike O\u2019Brien was the Foreign Office Minister charged with negotiating Britain's rapprochement with Libya in 2002 <ref>Kawczynski Daniel \u201cSeeking Gaddafi\u201d dialogue books, 2010 {{ISBN|978-1-906447-05-2}} p.35</ref> which led to Libya admitting responsibility for Lockerbie and paying compensation for victims, ending financial support for terrorism and an extensive chemical and nuclear weapons programme. \u201c\u2026the Americans thought it was entirely pointless exercise. We took the view that it would produce beneficial results\u2026 it was a calculated risk\u2026 are MI6 people did a tremendous job and the foreign office deserves a lot of credit\u2026 The Americans were absolutely stunned by this.\u201d <ref>Kawczynski Daniel \u201cSeeking Gaddafi\u201d dialogue books  2010 {{ISBN|978-1-906447-05-2}} p170</ref>\n\nConcerned by the abuse of human rights by the military leadership in Myanmar/Burma, O\u2019Brien successfully ran a campaign to get British American Tabacco to withdraw its investments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2003/nov/06/burma.politics|title=Tobacco giant quits Burma|first=Mark|last=Tran|date=6 November 2003|accessdate=18 May 2019|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2002, concerned by the human rights violations in Zimbabwe, O\u2019Brien called upon the England Cricket Board to cancel the participation of the England team in the World Cup match in that country; but he rejected demands for compensation for the cost of cancellation. He said, \u201cWe cannot order the ECB not to go to Zimbabwe, but we have asked them not to go\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/cricket-at-war-over-zimbabwe-tgfszrkpbzc|title=Cricket at war over Zimbabwe|first=By Greg Hurst and Daniel|last=McGrory|date=30 December 2002|accessdate=18 May 2019|via=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref> In February 2003, the England team confirmed it would not go to Zimbabwe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2395981/England-confirm-Zimbabwe-boycott.html|title=England confirm Zimbabwe boycott|first=|last=|date=10 February 2003|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=18 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Minister of State for Trade and Industry===\nHe was then appointed [[Minister of State]] for Trade and Industry, dealing with talks with the WTO as part of the Doha Round and helping to write the 2004 Trade White Paper.\n\n===Minister of State for E-commerce, Energy & Competitiveness===\nFollowing a reshuffle, he became Minister of State for E-commerce, Energy & Competitiveness at the [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Department of Trade and Industry]] on 9 September 2004.\n\n===Solicitor General for England and Wales===\nAfter the 2005 general election he replaced Harriet Harman as Solicitor General for England and Wales.\nMike O\u2019Brien had worked closely with the UK Jewish community to set up the first Holocaust Memorial Day in January 2001 and later in June 2005 he was asked to lead the British delegation to the OSCE Cordoba Conference on Anti-Semitism. Speaking at the conference he recalled, \u201c''As Race Equality Minister I helped introduce national Holocaust Memorial Day each year which demonstrates our commitment to eternal vigilance against the rise of intolerance''.\u201d and added that, \"''The British Government has also promoted an inclusive concept of citizenship. It allows people to be British but to be individuals and express their cultural identity. Our aim is integration, not assimilation. We welcome migrants and expect them to integrate, but on the basis of respect for their own identity.''\u201d<ref>https://www.osce.org/cio/15466?download=true</ref>\n\n===Minister of State for Pensions===\nOn 29 June 2007 he was appointed as [[Minister of State]] for Pension Reform in the [[Department for Work and Pensions]] under [[Secretary of State]] [[Peter Hain]]. Referring to the long running [[Ros Altmann#Pensionstheft campaign|Pensions Action Group campaign]] and speaking on the [[BBC Radio 4]] ''Moneybox'' programme on the day compensation was announced,  pensions expert [[Ros Altmann]], credited Peter Hain and O'Brien with \"having been very different to deal with than their predecessors and ... willing and eager to engage and find a way to sort this out.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/spl/hi/programmes/money_box/transcripts/07_12_22.pdf|publisher=BBC|title=MONEY BOX transcript page 4| date=7 December 2007|accessdate=25 April 2010}}</ref> The [[Pensions Act 2008]] completed its major stages whilst O' Brien was minister and received [[Royal Assent]] in November 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.epolitix.com/legislation/legislation-details/newsarticle/pensions-bill-2/|title=Pensions Act 2008|publisher=epolitics|accessdate=10 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Minister of State for Energy===\nOn 5 October 2008, he became [[Minister of State]] for Energy in order to help create the new [[Department of Energy and Climate Change]]. He took through Parliament two Energy Acts making reforms to take account of the Climate Change debate and to enable the building of new nuclear power stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/business-told-to-make-economic-case-for-new-nuclear-reactors-676702.html|title=Business told to make economic case for new nuclear reactors|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Minister of State for Health===\nIn June 2009, he became the Minister of State for Health.\nThrough administrative reforms of the NHS in two Acts of Parliament he firmly rejected a study commissioned from consultancy firm McKinsey and Company by his ministerial predecessor, which had recommended 137,000 jobs would need to go to make NHS efficiency savings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channel4.com/news/articles/uk/government+rejects+nhs+workforce+cuts/3330012.html|title=Government rejects NHS workforce cuts |work= Channel 4 News|accessdate=19 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nMike O\u2019Brien introduced priority NHS treatment for former service personnel injured in the line of duty and negotiated a settlement of compensation for the victims of Thalidomide.  Harold Evans, the former Editor of the Observer who had helped expose the Thalidomide scandal, said Mike O'Brien was one of the \u201cheroes for Justice\u201d in the Thalidomide story, adding, \u201cOn 14 January 2010 O'Brien made a dramatic announcement in Parliament. He apologised to the victims and their parents but he also committed the government to give \u00a320m to the Thalidomide Trust.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2012/sep/01/thalidomide-cover-up|title=Still no shame for thalidomide cover-up|first=Harold|last=Evans|date=1 September 2012|accessdate=19 May 2019|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n==After Parliament==\nIn June 2019, O'Brien was on the shortlist for the Labour candidate in the 2020 election for [[West Midlands Police and Crime Commissioner]]. There are four candidates on the Labour shortlist: himself, former Lord Mayor and Deputy West Midlands Police and Crime Commissioner [[Yvonne Mosquito]], a specialist housing and anti-social behaviour law solicitor Simon Foster, and a former assistant chief executive at [[Sandwell Metropolitan Borough Council|Sandwell Council]] Melanie Dudley.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/ex-city-mayor-yvonne-mosquito-16456663|title=Ex Brum mayor Yvonne Mosquito wants to be next police supremo for West Mids|last=Haynes|first=Jane|date=20 June 2019|website=birminghammail|accessdate=30 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mike O'Brien (UK politician)}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100220005307/http://www.mikeobrienfornorthwarwickshireandbedworth.com/ Official site]\n* [https://twitter.com/MikeOBrienMP Twitter stream]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071013193033/http://dwp.gov.uk/aboutus/ministers/mo%27brien.asp Department for Work and Pensions \u2013 Official Biography]\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-3938,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics \u2013 Ask Aristotle: Michael O'Brien MP]\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/mike_o'brien/north_warwickshire TheyWorkForYou.com \u2013 Mike O'Brien MP]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/mpdb/html/614.stm BBC Politics page]{{dead link|date=August 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-mike-obrien | Mike O'Brien }}\n\n===News items===\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/6902474.stm Pension reform in July 2007]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cornwall/4023341.stm Wave Hub plan in Cornwall in November 2004]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/3995311.stm UK embracing E-commerce in November 2004]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/2175314.stm Meeting Colonel Gaddafi in August 2002]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/1308514.stm 24 hour drinking in May 2001]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/706017.stm Accusing Home Office of racism in April 2000]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/449235.stm Accusing the Fire Service of racism in September 1999]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-par|uk}}\n{{Succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br />for [[North Warwickshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Warwickshire]]\n  | years = [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]]\u2013[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\n  | before = [[Francis Maude]]\n  | after = [[Dan Byles]]\n}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{Succession box\n  | title = [[Solicitor General for England and Wales]]\n  | years = 2005\u20132007\n  | before = [[Harriet Harman]]\n  | after=[[Vera Baird]]\n}}\n{{S-gov}}\n{{Succession box\n| title = [[Minister of State]] [[Home Office|for Immigration]]\n| years= 1997\u20132001\n| before= [[Emily Blatch]]\n| after = [[Barbara Roche]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| title = [[Minister of State]] [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|for Trade and Industry]]\n| years= 2001\u20132005\n| before= [[Nigel Griffiths]]\n| after = [[Ian McCartney]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| title = [[Minister of State]] [[Department for Work and Pensions|for Pensions]]\n| years = 2007\u20132008\n| before = [[John Hutton (Labour MP)|John Hutton]]\n| after = [[Rosie Winterton]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| title = [[Department of Energy and Climate Change|Minister of State for Energy]]\n| years = 2008\u20132009\n| before = [[Department of Energy and Climate Change|Office Created]]\n| after = [[Joan Ruddock]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| title = [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Minister for Health Services]]\n| years = 2009\u20132010\n| before = [[Ben Bradshaw]]\n| after = [[Simon Burns]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:OBrien, Mike}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1992\u20131997]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:Solicitors General for England and Wales]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Staffordshire University]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:English Roman Catholics]]\n", "name_user": "Alex B4", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mike_O%27Brien_(British_politician)"}
{"title_page": "Allan Jeayes", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n[[File:Actor_Allan_Jeayes.jpg|thumb|right|Allan Jeayes]]\n'''Allan John Jeayes''' (19 January 1885 &ndash; 20 September 1963) was an English stage and film actor.\n\nJeayes was born in [[London Borough of Barnet|Barnet]], [[Middlesex]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/results/world-records/england-and-wales-births-1837-2006?firstname=allan%20&lastname=jeayes |title=[Search] Results for England & Wales Births 1837-2006: Allan Jeayes |website=findmypast.co.uk}}</ref> the son of Isaac Herbert Jeayes, archivist and Assistant Keeper of Manuscripts at the British Museum.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Times/1939/Obituary/Isaac_Herbert_Jeayes|title=Obituary: I. H. Jeayes|date=30 March 1939|work=The Times |page=16|accessdate=12 September 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nJeayes was educated at [[Merchant Taylors' School, Northwood|Merchant Taylor's School]], and was originally a farmer, before making his stage debut in 1906.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lXnXDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA395&lpg=PA395&dq=allan+jeayes+The+Encyclopedia+of+British+Film:+Fourth+edition&source=bl&ots=E7U-uKJRMr&sig=6tjYdIM7MdRaDVZXFyKYoSiY5lY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwivvfCdz-XUAhXSKlAKHboYDyIQ6AEINDAD#v=onepage&q=allan+jeayes+The+Encyclopedia+of+British+Film:+Fourth+edition&f=false|title=The Encyclopedia of British Film: Fourth edition|first=Brian|last=McFarlane|date=16 May 2016|publisher=Oxford University Press|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nJeayes made his film debut in the 1918 ''Nelson'' as Sir [[William Hamilton (diplomat)|William Hamilton]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Low|first=Rachael|title=History of British Film (Volume 4): The History of the British Film 1918 - 1929|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6UbaAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA417|date=13 September 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781136206344|page=417}}</ref> He appeared in a number of films by producer [[Alexander Korda]]. His last film appearance was in 1962's ''[[Reach for Glory]]''. He starred as Howard Joyce in the original 1927 Broadway production of ''[[The Letter (play)|The Letter]]'' and played Sir Lawrence Wargarve in the 1943 London production of ''[[And Then There Were None (1943 play)|And Then There Were None]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wearing|first=J. P.|title=The London Stage 1940-1949: A Calendar of Productions, Performers, and Personnel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mreCBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA131|date=22 August 2014|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=9780810893061|page=131}}</ref>\n\nJeayes died on 20 September 1963, aged 78, in [[Marylebone]], London.\n\nThe [[National Portrait Gallery, London]], has two photographic portraits of him.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp50256/allan-jeayes |title=Allan Jeayes (1885-1963), Actor |publisher=National Portrait Gallery, London}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[Nelson (1918 film)|Nelson]]'' (1918) as [[William Hamilton (diplomat)|Sir William Hamilton]] (film debut)\n* ''[[Sherlock Holmes (Stoll film series)|The Solitary Cyclist]]'' (1921, Short) as Woodly\n* ''[[A Gentleman of France]]'' (1921) as [[Henry IV of France|Henry of Navarre]]\n* ''[[The Hound of the Baskervilles (1921 film)|The Hound of the Baskervilles]]'' (1921) as Dr. James Mortimer\n* ''[[The Missioner]]'' (1922) as Gilbert Deyes\n* ''[[The Third Round]]'' (1925) as Carl Peterson\n* ''[[The Hate Ship]]'' (1929) as Dr. Saunders\n* ''[[The Ghost Train (1931 film)|The Ghost Train]]'' (1931) as Dr. Sterling\n* ''[[Stranglehold (1931 film)|Stranglehold]]'' (1931) as King\n* ''[[Above Rubies]]'' (1932, Short) as Lamont\n* ''[[The Impassive Footman]]'' (1932) as John Marwood\n* ''[[Anne One Hundred]]'' (1933) as Penvale\n* ''[[Purse Strings]]'' (1933) as Walford\n* ''[[Paris Plane]]'' (1933) as Minor Role\n* ''[[Song of the Plough]]'' (1933) as Joe Saxby\n* ''Little Napoleon'' (1933, Short) as Shenstone \n* ''[[Eyes of Fate]]'' (1933) as Knocker\n* ''[[Ask Beccles]]'' (1933) as Matthew Blaise\n* ''[[The Rise of Catherine the Great]]'' (1934) as Colonel Karnilov\n* ''[[Colonel Blood (film)|Colonel Blood]]'' (1934) as [[Charles II of England|Charles II]]\n* ''[[Red Ensign (film)|Red Ensign]]'' (1934) as Grierson\n* ''[[The Camels are Coming (film)|The Camels are Coming]]'' (1934) as Sheikh\n* ''[[The Scarlet Pimpernel (1934 film)|The Scarlet Pimpernel]]'' (1934) as [[William Grenville, 1st Baron Grenville|Lord Grenville]]\n* ''[[Sanders of the River]]'' (1935) as Father O'Leary\n* ''[[Drake of England]]'' (1935) as [[Bernardino de Mendoza (Diplomat)|Don Bernardino]]\n* ''[[The Tunnel (1935 film)|The Tunnel]]'' (1935) as Steel Magnate (uncredited)\n* ''[[Koenigsmark (1935 film)|Koenigsmark]]'' (1935) as Grand Duke Rodolphe\n* ''[[King of the Damned]]'' (1935) as Dr. Prada\n* ''[[Things to Come]]'' (1936) as Mr. Cabal (uncredited)\n* ''[[Forget Me Not (1936 film)|Forget Me Not]]'' (1936) as London Theatre Manager\n* ''[[Seven Sinners (1936 film)|Seven Sinners]]'' (1936) as Heinrich Wagner\n* ''[[Crown v. Stevens]]'' (1936) as Inspector Carter\n* ''[[The House of the Spaniard]]'' (1936) as Don Pedro de Guzman\n* ''[[Rembrandt (1936 film)|Rembrandt]]'' (1936) as Doctor Tulp\n* ''[[His Lordship (1936 film)|His Lordship]]'' (1936) as Barak\n* ''[[Action for Slander]]'' (1937) as Colonel\n* ''[[Elephant Boy (film)|Elephant Boy]]'' (1937) as Machua Appa\n* ''[[The High Command]]'' (1937) as H.E., the Governor\n* ''[[Knight Without Armour]]'' (1937) as White General\n* ''[[The Squeaker (1937 film)|The Squeaker]]'' (1937) as Inspector Elford\n* ''[[Return of the Scarlet Pimpernel]]'' (1937) as Judge of the Tribunal\n* ''[[The Green Cockatoo]]'' (1937) as The Detective Inspector\n* ''[[I, Claudius (film)|I, Claudius]]'' (1937, Unreleased) as Musa, the emperor's physician\n* ''[[13 Men and a Gun]]'' (1938) as General Vloty\n* ''[[Dangerous Medicine]]'' (1938) as Supt. Fox\n* ''[[A Royal Divorce (1938 film)|A Royal Divorce]]'' (1938) as Marat\n* ''[[They Drive by Night (1938 film)|They Drive by Night]]'' (1938) as Wally Mason\n* ''[[Life of St. Paul]]'' (1938, Short) as Minor Role\n* ''[[Everything Happens to Me (1938 film)|Everything Happens to Me]]'' (1938)\n* ''[[Q Planes]]'' (1939) as Minor Role (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Four Feathers (1939 film)|The Four Feathers]]'' (1939) as General Faversham\n* ''[[Smith (1939 film)|Smith]]'' (1939, Short) as Employer\n* ''[[The Stars Look Down (film)|The Stars Look Down]]'' (1940) as Richard Barras\n* ''[[The Proud Valley]]'' (1940) as Mr. Trevor\n* ''[[The Spider (1940 film)|The Spider]]'' (1940) as George Hackett\n* ''[[Spy for a Day]]'' (1940) as Col. Roberts\n* ''[[The Good Old Days (film)|The Good Old Days]]'' (1940) as Shadwell\n* ''[[A Window in London]]'' (1940) as Sir Edward (uncredited)\n* ''[[Convoy (1940 film)|Convoy]]'' (1940) as Commander Blount\n* ''[[Night Train to Munich]]'' (1940) as Prisoner in Concentration Camp Lineup (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Flying Squad (1940 film)|The Flying Squad]]'' (1940) as Johnson\n* ''[[The Thief of Bagdad (1940 film)|The Thief of Bagdad]]'' (1940) as The Story Teller\n* ''[[Sailors Three]]'' (1940) as British Commander\n* ''[[You Will Remember]]'' (1941) as  Signor Foli\n* ''[[Old Bill and Son]]'' (1941) as Willoughby\n* ''[[Inspector Hornleigh Goes To It]]'' (1941) as Brigadier Lloyd (uncredited)\n* ''[[\"Pimpernel\" Smith]]'' (1941) as Dr Benckendorf\n* ''[[Uncensored (film)|Uncensored]]'' (1942) (uncredited)\n* ''[[Talk About Jacqueline]]'' (1942) (uncredited)\n* ''[[Tomorrow We Live (1943 film)|Tomorrow We Live]]'' (1943) as Pogo\n* ''[[The Shipbuilders]]'' (1943) as Ralph\n* ''[[Dead of Night]]'' (1945) as Maurice Olcott (segment \"The Ventiloquist's Dummy\")\n* ''[[Perfect Strangers (1945 film)|Perfect Strangers]]'' (1945) as Commander\n* ''[[Lisbon Story (1946 film)|Lisbon Story]]'' (1946) as Dr. Cartier\n* ''[[The Man Within (film)|The Man Within]]'' (1947) as Judge\n* ''[[Blanche Fury]]'' (1948) as Mr. Weatherby\n* ''[[Saraband for Dead Lovers]]'' (1948) as Governor of Ahlden\n* ''[[Obsession (1949 film)|Obsession]]'' (1949) as Clubman #2\n* ''[[The Reluctant Widow (film)|The Reluctant Widow]]'' (1950) as Colonel\n* ''The Song in the Forest'' (1950, TV Movie) as [[Franz Joseph I of Austria|Emperor Franz Josef]]\n* ''[[Waterfront (1950 film)|Waterfront]]'' (1950) as Prison officer\n* ''[[Reach for Glory]]'' (1962) as Crabtree (final film)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n*{{IMDb name|id=0420011}}\n*{{IBDB name}}\n*{{Find a Grave|18089884|accessdate=14 September 2010}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jeayes, Allan}}\n[[Category:1885 births]]\n[[Category:1963 deaths]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n[[File:Actor_Allan_Jeayes.jpg|thumb|right|Allan Jeayes]]\n'''Allan John Jeayes''' (19 January 1885 &ndash; 20 September 1963) was an English stage and film actor.\n\nJeayes was born in [[London Borough of Barnet|Barnet]], [[Middlesex]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/results/world-records/england-and-wales-births-1837-2006?firstname=allan%20&lastname=jeayes |title=[Search] Results for England & Wales Births 1837-2006: Allan Jeayes |website=findmypast.co.uk}}</ref> the son of Isaac Herbert Jeayes, archivist and Assistant Keeper of Manuscripts at the British Museum.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Times/1939/Obituary/Isaac_Herbert_Jeayes|title=Obituary: I. H. Jeayes|date=30 March 1939|work=The Times |page=16|accessdate=12 September 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nJeayes was educated at [[Merchant Taylors' School, Northwood|Merchant Taylor's School]], and was originally a farmer, before making his stage debut in 1906.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lXnXDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA395&lpg=PA395&dq=allan+jeayes+The+Encyclopedia+of+British+Film:+Fourth+edition&source=bl&ots=E7U-uKJRMr&sig=6tjYdIM7MdRaDVZXFyKYoSiY5lY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwivvfCdz-XUAhXSKlAKHboYDyIQ6AEINDAD#v=onepage&q=allan+jeayes+The+Encyclopedia+of+British+Film:+Fourth+edition&f=false|title=The Encyclopedia of British Film: Fourth edition|first=Brian|last=McFarlane|date=16 May 2016|publisher=Oxford University Press|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nJeayes made his film debut in the 1918 ''Nelson'' as Sir [[William Hamilton (diplomat)|William Hamilton]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Low|first=Rachael|title=History of British Film (Volume 4): The History of the British Film 1918 - 1929|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6UbaAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA417|date=13 September 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781136206344|page=417}}</ref> He appeared in a number of films by producer [[Alexander Korda]]. His last film appearance was in 1962's ''[[Reach for Glory]]''. He starred as Howard Joyce in the original 1927 Broadway production of ''[[The Letter (play)|The Letter]]'' and played Sir Lawrence Wargarve in the 1943 London production of ''[[And Then There Were None (1943 play)|And Then There Were None]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wearing|first=J. P.|title=The London Stage 1940-1949: A Calendar of Productions, Performers, and Personnel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mreCBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA131|date=22 August 2014|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=9780810893061|page=131}}</ref>\n\nJeayes died on 20 September 1963, aged 78, in [[Marylebone]], London.\n\nThe [[National Portrait Gallery, London]], has two photographic portraits of him.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp50256/allan-jeayes |title=Allan Jeayes (1885-1963), Actor |publisher=National Portrait Gallery, London}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[Nelson (1918 film)|Nelson]]'' (1918) as [[William Hamilton (diplomat)|Sir William Hamilton]] (film debut)\n* ''[[Sherlock Holmes (Stoll film series)|The Solitary Cyclist]]'' (1921, Short) as Woodly\n* ''[[A Gentleman of France]]'' (1921) as [[Henry IV of France|Henry of Navarre]]\n* ''[[The Hound of the Baskervilles (1921 film)|The Hound of the Baskervilles]]'' (1921) as Dr. James Mortimer\n* ''[[The Missioner]]'' (1922) as Gilbert Deyes\n* ''[[The Third Round]]'' (1925) as Carl Peterson\n* ''[[The Hate Ship]]'' (1929) as Dr. Saunders\n* ''[[The Ghost Train (1931 film)|The Ghost Train]]'' (1931) as Dr. Sterling\n* ''[[Stranglehold (1931 film)|Stranglehold]]'' (1931) as King\n* ''[[Above Rubies]]'' (1932, Short) as Lamont\n* ''[[The Impassive Footman]]'' (1932) as John Marwood\n* ''[[Anne One Hundred]]'' (1933) as Penvale\n* ''[[Purse Strings]]'' (1933) as Walford\n* ''[[Paris Plane]]'' (1933) as Minor Role\n* ''[[Song of the Plough]]'' (1933) as Joe Saxby\n* ''Little Napoleon'' (1933, Short) as Shenstone \n* ''[[Eyes of Fate]]'' (1933) as Knocker\n* ''[[Ask Beccles]]'' (1933) as Matthew Blaise\n* ''[[The Rise of Catherine the Great]]'' (1934) as Colonel Karnilov\n* ''[[Colonel Blood (film)|Colonel Blood]]'' (1934) as [[Charles II of England|Charles II]]\n* ''[[Red Ensign (film)|Red Ensign]]'' (1934) as Grierson\n* ''[[The Camels are Coming (film)|The Camels are Coming]]'' (1934) as Sheikh\n* ''[[The Scarlet Pimpernel (1934 film)|The Scarlet Pimpernel]]'' (1934) as [[William Grenville, 1st Baron Grenville|Lord Grenville]]\n* ''[[Sanders of the River]]'' (1935) as Father O'Leary\n* ''[[Drake of England]]'' (1935) as [[Bernardino de Mendoza (Diplomat)|Don Bernardino]]\n* ''[[The Tunnel (1935 film)|The Tunnel]]'' (1935) as Steel Magnate (uncredited)\n* ''[[Koenigsmark (1935 film)|Koenigsmark]]'' (1935) as Grand Duke Rodolphe\n* ''[[King of the Damned]]'' (1935) as Dr. Prada\n* ''[[Things to Come]]'' (1936) as Mr. Cabal (uncredited)\n* ''[[Forget Me Not (1936 film)|Forget Me Not]]'' (